03811nmm a2200553Ia 9780791477953DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914779537 a10.1515/97807914779532doi  a(DE-B1597)683227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB2430.B43bM67 2008 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1941 aMoulard-Leonard, Valentine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBergson-Deleuze Encounters :bTranscendental Experience and the Thought of the Virtual /cValentine Moulard-Leonard. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (208 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Contemporary French Thought00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tVirtual Empiricism: The Revaluation of the Transcendental -- tBergson's Genealogy of Consciousness -- tIntroducing Memory: From the Psychological to the Virtual -- tThe Unconscious as Ontology of the Virtual -- tBetween Bergson and Deleuze: The Method of Intuition as Transcendental/Virtual Empiricism -- tCinematic Thought: The Deleuzean Image and the Crystals of Time -- tProust and Thought: Death,Art, and the Adventures of the Involuntary -- tBergson-Deleuze Encounters: Machinic Becomings and Virtual Materialism -- tNotes -- tReference -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBergson-Deleuze Encounters sheds light on the intricate bond between French philosophers Henri Bergson and Gilles Deleuze. It explores the major diffraction between the two thinkers, conveys a sense of the irreducible originality of Deleuze's thought, and offers a detailed account of Bergson's "Copernican Revolution." In so doing, it presents an explanation of thought and experience that contrasts with the dominant account of the phenomenological tradition. Valentine Moulard-Leonard argues that Bergson and Deleuze share a novel conception of the transcendental—which they call the Virtual—that marks a new era in thinking, in which what is ultimately at stake is a new vision of time, experience, and materiality. The Virtual provides an indispensable alternative to the totalizing systems spawned by the traditional transcendent image of thought—be they systems of idealism, scientific positivism, nationalism, racism, sexism, or dogmatism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Postmodernism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147795340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477953/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles